==English==
===Etymology===
From Middle English '''worm''' < Old English '''[[wyrm]]''' (serpent, dragon, worm) < Proto-Germanic '''[[*wurmiz]]''' < Proto-Indo-European '''[[*wrmi-]]'''/'''[[*wrmo-]]''' (serpent, scorpion, maggot, worm), possibly from PIE base '''[[*wer-]]''' (to turn).

===Pronunciation===
* ''[[RP]]:'' {{IPA|/wɜːm/}}, {{SAMPA|/w3:m/}}
* ''US:'' {{AHD|wûrm}}, {{IPA|/wɝm/}}, {{SAMPA|/w3`m/}}
*{{audio|en-us-worm.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:'''Rhymes''': [[Rhymes:English:-ɜː(r)m|-ɜː(r)m]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun|worm|worms}}

#{{countable}} A generally [[tubular]] [[invertebrate]] of the [[annelid]] [[phylum]].
#{{countable}} A [[contemptible]] or devious person.
#:''Don't try to run away, you little worm!''
#{{countable}} {{computing}} A [[self-replicating program]] that propagates widely through a network.
#{{cricket}} A [[graphical]] [[representation]] of the [[total]] [[run]]s [[score]]d in an [[innings]].
#The [[thread]] of a [[screw]].
#{{countable}} {{archaic}} A [[dragon]] or [[mythology|mythological]] [[serpent]].

